    \section*{Abstract}
This paper discusses the possibility of grounding L.E.J Brouwer’s intuitionism on Edmund Husserl’s phenomenology and, in light of certain arguments by Jaakko Hintikka, ultimately reaches the conclusion that such a grounding is not possible. Firstly, Brouwer’s and Husserl’s different positions will be outlined, revealing, among other things, why Brouwer rejects the Law of the Excluded Middle and which consequences this has for mathematics - his choice sequences being of particular interest. Also, a number of important concepts from Husserl’s phenomenology, such as intuition, intuition of essence and intentionality, will be analyzed. Secondly, it will be discussed whether Mark Van Atten’s argument for the possibility of giving the choice sequences a phenomenological fundation is sound. Van Atten shows how both Husserl’s and Brouwer’s philosophy of mathematics are insufficient to create a proper foundation for mathematics. Therefore, he tries to recreate parts of Brouwer’s intuitionism on Husserl’s phenomenology. Finally, an argument by Hintikka is outlined, showing how the difference between Husserl's and Brouwer's conceptions of intuition are too great to achieve van Atten's goal, i.e. to reconstruct Brouwer’s position on a phenomenological foundation.
